# TypeScript Rules
- Strict mode is enabled — honor all strict checks
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- Use `type` for unions, intersections, and primitives
- Never use non-null assertion (`!`) — handle nullability explicitly
- Use `unknown` instead of `any`; narrow the type before use
- Define return types on all exported functions
- Use Zod for runtime validation of external data (API responses, form input)